@eval-runner @guardkit-vs-vanilla
Feature: Eval Runner — GuardKit vs Vanilla Comparison Pipeline
  As an eval operator
  I want to run automated A/B comparisons of GuardKit pipeline vs vanilla Claude Code
  So that I can measure whether GuardKit produces measurably better results than plain Claude Code

  Background:
    Given the eval runner is connected to NATS JetStream
    And workspace templates "guardkit-project" and "plain-project" are available
    And the Anthropic API is reachable for the LLM judge

  # ============================================================================
  # GROUP A: Key Examples
  # ============================================================================

  # Why: Core end-to-end path — a brief with text input runs both arms and produces a scored comparison result
  @key-example @smoke
  Scenario: A guardkit_vs_vanilla eval brief with text input completes end-to-end
    Given a YAML eval brief with type "guardkit_vs_vanilla"
    And the input source is "text" containing a feature requirement
    When the eval runner processes the brief
    Then two workspaces should be provisioned from different templates
    And both workspaces should contain an identical "input.txt"
    And the GuardKit arm should execute the full pipeline
    And the vanilla arm should execute bare Claude Code
    And a scored comparison result should be produced
    And the result should include per-criterion delta scores

  # Why: Demonstrates workspace forking — the foundation of fair comparison
  @key-example @smoke
  Scenario: Workspaces are provisioned independently from their respective templates
    Given a guardkit_vs_vanilla eval brief
    When workspaces are provisioned
    Then the GuardKit workspace should contain "CLAUDE.md" and ".guardkit/" configuration
    And the vanilla workspace should contain the same codebase structure
    And the vanilla workspace should not contain "CLAUDE.md"
    And the vanilla workspace should not contain ".guardkit/"
    And both workspaces should have a ".eval/evidence/" directory

  # Why: Input identity is critical — both arms must receive exactly the same requirement text
  @key-example
  Scenario: Both arms receive identical input text
    Given a brief with input source "text" containing "Add a GET endpoint for channel stats"
    When the input is resolved and distributed to workspaces
    Then the GuardKit workspace "input.txt" should match the vanilla workspace "input.txt" exactly

  # Why: Sequential arm execution prevents API contention
  @key-example
  Scenario: Arms execute sequentially with status updates between them
    Given a guardkit_vs_vanilla eval brief
    When the eval runner processes the brief
    Then the GuardKit arm should complete before the vanilla arm starts
    And a status message "arm_a_complete" should be published between arms
    And a status message "arm_b_running" should be published when the vanilla arm starts

  # Why: Delta scoring is the core differentiation — absolute quality is irrelevant
  @key-example @smoke
  Scenario: The judge scores criteria as deltas between arms
    Given both arms have completed and produced evidence files
    When the judge evaluates the comparison
    Then each criterion should be scored between 0.0 and 1.0
    And a score of 1.0 should mean GuardKit clearly outperformed vanilla
    And a score of 0.5 should mean the arms performed equally
    And a score of 0.0 should mean vanilla equalled or outperformed GuardKit
    And the weighted score should be the sum of criterion scores multiplied by their weights

  # Why: Metrics extraction grounds LLM judging in quantitative data
  @key-example
  Scenario: Quantitative metrics are extracted from both workspaces after arm completion
    Given the GuardKit arm has written evidence files with coverage, lint, and assumption counts
    And the vanilla arm has written evidence files with coverage, lint, and assumption counts
    When metrics are extracted
    Then the comparison should include a coverage delta
    And the comparison should include a lint violation delta
    And the comparison should include an assumption surfacing delta

