  # GROUP B: Boundary Conditions
  # ============================================================================

  # Why: Just-inside boundary — score at exactly the pass threshold should pass
  # [ASSUMPTION: confidence=high] Pass threshold is 0.65 as specified in EVAL-007 brief
  @boundary
  Scenario: An eval with a weighted score exactly at the pass threshold passes
    Given a brief with pass_threshold 0.65
    And criterion scores that produce a weighted score of exactly 0.65
    When the result is classified
    Then the eval status should be "PASSED"

  # Why: Just-outside boundary — score just below pass threshold should fail (not escalate)
  @boundary @negative
  Scenario: An eval with a weighted score just below the pass threshold fails
    Given a brief with pass_threshold 0.65
    And criterion scores that produce a weighted score of 0.64
    When the result is classified
    Then the eval status should be "FAILED"

  # Why: Just-inside boundary — score at exactly the escalate threshold should fail (not escalate)
  # [ASSUMPTION: confidence=high] Escalate threshold is 0.40 as specified in EVAL-007 brief
  @boundary
  Scenario: An eval with a weighted score exactly at the escalate threshold fails but is not escalated
    Given a brief with escalate_threshold 0.40
    And criterion scores that produce a weighted score of exactly 0.40
    When the result is classified
    Then the eval status should be "FAILED"
    And the result should not be published to the escalation topic

  # Why: Just-outside boundary — score below escalate threshold triggers human escalation
  @boundary @negative
  Scenario: An eval with a weighted score below the escalate threshold is escalated
    Given a brief with escalate_threshold 0.40
    And criterion scores that produce a weighted score of 0.39
    When the result is classified
    Then the eval status should be "ESCALATED"
    And the result should be published to the escalation topic for human review

  # Why: Timeout boundary — arm must respect the per-arm timeout
  # [ASSUMPTION: confidence=high] Per-arm timeout is total_timeout / 2 as stated in architecture doc
  @boundary
  Scenario Outline: Arm execution respects the per-arm timeout derived from brief
    Given a brief with timeout_minutes <total_timeout>
    When the per-arm timeout is calculated
    Then each arm should have a timeout of <per_arm_seconds> seconds

    Examples:
      | total_timeout | per_arm_seconds |
      | 90            | 2700            |
      | 60            | 1800            |
      | 30            | 900             |

  # Why: Max turns boundary — arm execution respects max_turns_per_arm
  @boundary
  Scenario: Arm execution stops at the max_turns_per_arm limit
    Given a brief with max_turns_per_arm 100
    When an arm reaches 100 turns without completing
    Then the arm should stop and record what was produced
    And the arm should not be marked as errored

  # Why: Metrics boundary — missing evidence files produce -1 (not measurable), not errors
  @boundary
  Scenario: Missing evidence files produce not-measurable metrics rather than errors
    Given the GuardKit arm completed but did not write ".eval/evidence/c2.txt"
    When metrics are extracted
    Then the GuardKit arm test coverage should be reported as "not measurable"
    And the coverage delta should be reported as "not measurable"
    And the extraction should not raise an error

  # Why: Boundary — both arms produce identical results (perfect tie)
  @boundary
  Scenario: A perfect tie produces a weighted score of 0.5
    Given both arms produced identical test coverage, lint violations, and assumption counts
    And the LLM judge scored all criteria as 0.5
    When the weighted score is calculated
    Then the weighted score should be exactly 0.5

